    <h3 id="tribute-heading">Here is a timeline of Terry's life:</h3>
    <p id="tribute-info">
    <ul>
      <li><strong>1958</strong> - Terry Fox was born in Winnipeg, Manitoba to Rolland and Betty Fox</li>
      <li><strong>1968</strong> - His family settled in Port Coquitlam, BC, Canada</li>
      <li><strong>1976</strong> - He was distracted while driving and crashed into the back of a pickup truck resulting in an injury to his right knee </li>
      <li><strong>1977</strong> - He was diagnosed with osteosarcoma, a rare form a cancer that often starts in the knees </li>
      <li><strong>1977</strong> - He was told that his right knee would have to be amputated and that he had a 50% chance of survival</li>
      <li><strong>1978</strong> - He began a 14-month training program to compete in a 17-mile road race</li>
      <li><strong>1979</strong> - Terry finishes last pace in the road race but is met with applause from the audience</li>
      <li><strong>1980</strong> - Fox begins his Marathon for Hope, with the goal of running across Canada to raise money for cancer research</li>
      <li><strong>1980</strong> - Fox finishes Nova Scotia and Quebec and begins his run through Ontario</li>
      <li><strong>1980</strong> - He is forced to stop his run across Canada due to his cancer returning</li>
      <li><strong>1981</strong> - Terry Fox receives the Order of the Dogwood - the highest provincial award</li>
      <li><strong>1981</strong> - Terry Fox dies at the Royal Columbian Hospital</li>
    </ul>
    <p id="tribute-message">It occurs very rarely in the life of a nation that the courageous spirit of one person unites all people in the celebration of his life and in the mourning of his death ... We do not think of him as one who was defeated by misfortune but as one who inspired us with the example of the triumph of the human spirit over adversity".</p>
    <p id="cite"> - Canadian Prime Minister Pierre Trudeau</c>
